    {
      "title": "Introduction to Past Tense Verbs",
      "titleArabic": "الْفِعْلُ الْمَاضِي",
      "content": [
        "Arabic verbs in the past tense (al-fi'l al-māḍī) are built from a three-letter root. The basic form (third person masculine singular) adds the pattern فَعَلَ to the root.",
        "When the subject follows the verb, the sentence structure is: Verb + Subject + Object. This is the default word order for verbal sentences in Arabic."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Past tense verbs end in فَتْحَة (a-sound): ذَهَبَ, كَتَبَ, قَرَأَ",
        "The basic form is 'he did' - other forms are derived from this",
        "Verbal sentences typically start with the verb",
        "ذَهَبَ الطَّالِبُ - the student went (verb first)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "ذَهَبَ", "english": "he went" },
        { "arabic": "كَتَبَ", "english": "he wrote" },
        { "arabic": "قَرَأَ", "english": "he read" },
        { "arabic": "ذَهَبَ الطَّالِبُ إِلَى الْمَسْجِدِ", "english": "The student went to the mosque" }
      ]
    }
  ],
